<subSubSection pageId="247" pageNumber="247" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="247.[128,654,257,1759]" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">
DIAGNOSIS: Distinguished by the black apices of the femora (figs. 12, 13), the usually mixed vestiture of simple and some sericeous silvery setae (fig. 63B, C, pl. 4R) or with vestiture of only simple dense silvery (fig. 59B, pl. 4G), or moderately dense brown setae (pl. 4L), the usually medial, long, pointed, and undivided tergal process (figs. 57H, 60F, 64M, N, 65G), and the produced, rounded, medial surface of the interramal lobe usually with a relatively long, ventral projection (figs. 58D, 62B, 66B, 70D). The structure of the endosomal spicule is unique to this species group, particularly the basal origin of the dorsal lobe on the far left margin of the ventral lobe and the widely separated bifurcate rami of the dorsal and ventral lobes (figs. 60A, 64A–C, 65C–F). In comparison to other 
<taxonomicName box="[381,607,790,813]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[381,518,790,813]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">Slaterocoris</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
the costal margins of both sexes of most of the species are usually more elongate and parallel sided (pls. 1–3) (except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Carvalho and China" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[417,562,880,901]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis box="[417,562,880,901]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); the hemelytron of the female is more arcuate than in the male. All the species contained in this group have exclusively Mexican distributions (map 12).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="247" pageNumber="247" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="247.[128,654,257,1759]" lastBlockId="247.[701,1228,213,649]" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">
DISCUSSION: Two ambiguous characters— the tergal process long and usually undivided (23-3) and the basal lobe of the right paramere with a short serrate process (44- 4)—support the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Carvalho and China" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[321,430,1147,1168]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis box="[321,430,1147,1168]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group on figure 2. Three characters provide unambiguous, homoplasious support to the species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Carvalho and China" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[128,237,1235,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis box="[128,237,1235,1256]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group when two of the three most parsimonious cladograms (fig. 1A, B) are considered. The apical portion of the femur in all species is black (5-1). Such femoral coloration is also found in species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kelton, 1968:" authorityYear="1134" box="[128,236,1383,1404]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argenteus">
<emphasis box="[128,236,1383,1404]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">argenteus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group and in 
<taxonomicName box="[445,583,1382,1405]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Strongylocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[445,583,1382,1405]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The slightly convex anteromedial surface of the second gonapophyses (62-0) seen in this group, also occurs elsewhere in the genus and several outgroup taxa. The interramal lobe with a concave medial surface and a long, ventral projection (69-2), found in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Carvalho and China" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[128,237,1590,1611]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis box="[128,237,1590,1611]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group also occurs in several other 
<taxonomicName box="[128,371,1618,1641]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[128,264,1618,1641]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">Slaterocoris</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
Mixed vestiture with simple and some sericeous setae (12-1), seen on most of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Carvalho and China" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[333,441,1679,1700]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis box="[333,441,1679,1700]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group species, is common in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Forero" baseAuthorityYear="2008" box="[331,462,1708,1730]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Orthotylini">Orthotylini</taxonomicName>
and occurs on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Carvalho and Schaffner" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[128,374,1736,1759]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Josephinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reinhardi">
<emphasis box="[128,374,1736,1759]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">Josephinus reinhardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A medially located tergal process (70-2) supports the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Carvalho and China" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[1119,1228,213,234]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis box="[1119,1228,213,234]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group but is homoplastic, as the same state occurs in the species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" box="[1014,1136,271,294]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Josephinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1014,1136,271,294]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">Josephinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is reversed in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" box="[842,999,301,324]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tanydexios">
<emphasis box="[842,999,301,324]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. tanydexios</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(70-1). In three 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Carvalho and China" baseAuthorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" box="[1016,1175,330,353]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculatus">
<emphasis box="[1016,1175,330,353]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Carvalho and China" baseAuthorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" box="[883,1008,360,383]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis box="[883,1008,360,383]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. clavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the height of the ventroanterior margin of the vestibulum is somewhat deeper (57-5) than in other 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">Slaterocoris</emphasis>
species.
</taxonomicName>
This character state contributes support to a sister-group relationship between the former two species and is autapomorphic in the latter species. The sister-group relationship of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" box="[851,1004,567,590]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculatus">
<emphasis box="[851,1004,567,590]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. maculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwartz" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Carvalho and China" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[1079,1228,568,589]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Slaterocoris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="247" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus">
<emphasis box="[1079,1228,568,589]" italics="true" pageId="247" pageNumber="247">S. punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
receives additionally support from moderately dense dorsal vestiture (10-1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
